{"/service/ndnp/ncu/batch_ncu_grandfather_ver01/data/sn99061556/00415667474/1910061401/0380.xml":{"full_text":";Wwi;Ji-Si..ft'':iT-\nI\n-i\nTHE FARMER AND MECHANIC\nUNPATRIOTIC ACT\n4\nX\ni\nV\nt\nOF BILLS\nt\n9\ni\nWEEK HAS\nIBM\nBEEN\nCotton advanced in Face\nGood Weather Reports\nDUE TO COVERING SHORTS\nKsperialy Wa3 This True of the Sum\nmer MonUis, Options Bein Over\nsold Owing to Favorable WosUher\nJtciKrts Stock of Oerti floated Cot\nton Itapidly Decreasing.\n(By the Associated Press.)\nNew York, June 10. Cotton has ad\nvanced in the face of weather condi\ntions over most sections that have\nbeen practically ideal Covering by\nlarge Wall Street shorts have been the\ngreat feature so far as the summer\nmonths are concerned. The next crop\nmonths did not move materially until\nThursday, when there was a sharp ad\nvance. These options had evidently\nbecome over-sold owing to the favor\nable weather and the many reports of\nsteady progress of the plant. Yet of\nlate excessive rains have occurred in\nmany parts of the belt while in Texas\nmaximum temperatures have been\nreported of 100 to 104 degrees. These\nconditions have caused considerable\ncovering and there has also been not\na little new buying on the idea that\nquotations for the new crop months\nare too low when compared with the\nprices ruling for the summer months.\nThe stock of certificated cotton here\nhas decreased at the rate of 5,000 to\n3 0.000 bales daily and thus far this\nmonth has diminished over 54,000\ntales. As leading bulls are reported\nto have sold the bulk of their holdings\nof spot cotton it is predicted that the\n.stock will continue to dwindle as fast\nas freight room can be engaged. The\nLiverpool spot market has been active\nwith spot and call transactions of as\nhigh as 17,000 bales in a single day.\nManchester is reported active.\nLarge sales of the actual cotton\nhave been officially reported here in\nNew York. According to some Liver\npool people the sales of spot cotton\nthere would be larger if desirable cot\nton was available. Increasing reports\nof the appearance of boll weevil have\nb en received from Mississippi, Loui\nsiana and Alabama. The crop is re\nported to be from two to three weeks\nlate in many sections and the plant\nwill be exposed to a greater degree\nthan usual to weevil damage. A large\ncrop is undoubtedly needed. On the\nother hand the weather has been in\nthe main favorable, and crop reports,\nin many cases, more cheerful. Trade\nreports from most sections of the\ncountry have been unfavorable. The\naction of the American Printing Com\njwiny at Fall River in deciding to close\ndown indefinitely has been followed\nby the annoucement that the big Fall\n'.liver Iron Work, the print cloth\nplant owned by M. C. D. Borden, will\nphut down every other week for an In\ndefinite term. At Charlotte, N. C, a\nmovement has been started looking to\na complete shut-down of the yarn\nmills there. Leading bulls have liqui\ndated to some eextent on the advance\nand there has been considerable selling\nattributed to Jas. A. Patten. But the\ndominant factor has been active cov\nering of shorts, large and small.\nNEW IMPROVED LOW STEP-OVER\niffrfiJZZZ 52te?yPt known to mechanics.\neconamyandsZ1 W v J? by ltSlf Ior durability, convenience,\nand SltoSSXw -V 6 mke th,em n?ounted an unmounted. ive the best priced\njtnt party, write us immediate I v for ratalno-\nWOODRUFF MACHINERY MANUFACTURING COMPANY. Winder, Ga.\nwhile the miscellaneous export trade Total exports\ni-umnues quiei Dut rairly steady.\nValues are generally steadier.\nTrade in foot-wear continues quiet.\nCOTTON BECEIPTS.\nNew York, June 10. The following are\nthe total net receipts of cotton at all ports\nsince .September 1st:\nGalveston 2 450.991\nNew Orleans iiJoL21K)\nMobile '241350\nSavannah i.siSftS\nCharleston 208,145\nWilmington 310,580\nNorfolk 500,917\nBaltimore 71,704\nNew York fr'urt\nBoston l.'i,215\nNewport News 12,014\nPhiladelphia 1,600\nSan Francisco 57,712\nBrunswick 227,253\nPort Town send 32,552\nPensacola 136,030\nPortland, Ore. 200\nPortArt&ur and Sabine Pass 141.t50\nJacksonville '20..T00\nKagle Pass, Texas 620\nEl Paso, Texas 5G5\nLaredo, Texas 1,742\nOulfport 8.264\nGeorgetown 1,370\nTexas City 20,708\nMinor Ports 12,005\nTotal 7,080,07\nWeekly Interior Cotton Towns.\nSanv date last vftir.7.Sft4.91fi\nsmock at an united states ports 408,539\nStock at all United States ports\nsame time last year 4GK.503\nStock at all interior towns 216,523\nStock at all Interior towns, same\ntime last 3-ear 227.898\nStock at Liverpool 505i000\nStock at Liverpool same time last\n-vear 1,163,000\nStock of American afloat for Great\nBritain same time last year 75,000\nLiverpool Weekly Cotton.\nLiverpool, June 10. The following are\nthe weekly cotton statistics\nImports, all kinds, 44.000 bales.\nImports, American. 30,000.\nStock, all kinds, 505,000.\nStock, American, 45,000.\nAmerican forwarded 51,000.\nTotal exports 4,000\nTotal sales, all kinds, 00.000.\nTotal sales, American, 61,000.\nEnglish spinners takings, 57,000.\nTotal export, 5,000.\nQuantity afloat, American, 03.000.\nQuantity afloat, American, 53.000.\nTotal sales of speculators, 3,300.\nTotal sales to exporters, IKK).\nThe sales include 3.330 bales called\nor sold prior to February 12.\nDAUGHTERS OF CONFEDERACY.\nNew York, June 10.\nTowns. Tone. Mid. ltects.\nAthens 40\nAtlanta uoni. 14 3-4\nBrenham\nCharlotte steady 14 3-1\nColumbia\nColumbus, Ga firm 14 3-4\nColumbus, Miss\nEufaula\nGreenville\nHelena\nLittle Rock\nMacon\nMeridian\nMontgomery steady 14 3-4\nNashville quiet 15\nNatchez\nNewberry\nIlaleigh\nBorne\n53\n25\n27\nJ70\n45\n77\n17\no\n2.(\n20\n108\n40\n?i\n20\nSelma\nShreveport firm\nYicksburg\n14 1-4\n330\n208\n40\n350\nComparative Cotton Statement.\nNew York, June 10. For the week end\ning Friday, June 10.\nNet receipts at nil U. S. ports dur\ning week 20,123\nNet receipts at all TT. S. ports\nsame week last year 51,023\nTotal receipts since September 1 st 7,080,075\nTotal receipts to same date last\nyear 9,701.910,\nRvnnrts for the week 7S.608\"\nExports for same week last year. 60,2021\nTotal exports since September 1 st. 5,621, 848\nWeldon, June 11. No more de\nlightful afternoon could he imagined\nthan the meeting of the Junius\nDaniel Chapter United Daughters of\nthe Confederacy with Miss Susann\nZollicoffer on Friday. The beautiful\nhome was artistically decorated with\nlilies and long leaf pine, the color\nscheme being yellow and green. At\nthe conclusion of the business session\na most delightful program was ren\ndered as follows:\nWhen the Heart Was Young Miss\nPhelps.\nKntertaining President Davis, read\ning, Mrs. Wjlkins.\nTenting Quartette Misses Phelps,\nZollicoffer, Pierce, and Mrs. It. S.\nTravis.\nReconstruction under Johnson\nMiss Pierce.\nA GUIS AT DIS\nCOVERY. DROPSY.\nCUBED with veg\netable remedies\nremove all symp\ntoms of dropsy in\n8 to 20 days; 30 to\n00 days effect per\nmanent cure. Trial\ntreatment furnish\ned free to every\nsufferer; noth\ning fairer. For\ncirculars a n d\ntestlmo nials\nand free trial\ntreatment write\nDr. II. II. Green's Sons. Hos V. Atlanta, Ga\nft\" 1 1\nEVERY FARMER SHOULD READ\nmwvs wkkkijY rkvjew.\nV:th Good Ontlook for AVheat and\ntton Crops the Business Outlook\nimproves.\nU?y the Associated Press.)\nNew York, June 10. R. G. Dunn\nmpany's Weekly Review of Trade\ntomorrow will say:\nWith a compromise effected on the\nquestion of railroad rates which,\nthough depending in part on action\nhy Congress on the railroad bill, is\nsgarded as satisfactory, and with\nTop prospects for both wheat and\ncotton decidedly good, the business\noutlook shows much improvement\nvcr last week.\nStorks' of pig iron continue to ac\ncumulate, yet curtailment of produc\ner) was on a much less extensive\nde during May than in the preced\nent.' mnntVi vT 1\n1 t w uusinpj riimfts r-\nand a\nthe\n.uked-of cancellations of equipment\n,;rs J?ave not materialized and the\nw 7s cntinue to place some im\n1 jrtant contracts in certain lines,\ndurr r notice from the largest pro\nun in? ctton and woolen goods of\nverv ntlon to curtail production\ntie i-!?atenally bespeaks the difficul-\nniencp \"lnfir textile llnes as a conse\nalHl t, or tn sub-normal demand\ny thVPressure upon costs induced\nraw irL!111 and uncertain values on\nM aterial3.\n1'mitaUfacturers are purchasing in a\nrea?, waf; and there is some in\ncall for stanle domestics\nAND THE\nWeekly News and Observer\ni\nW ,n sliffhtly larger volume, an\nucr feeling exists as a result of\nompromise rcgardi freight ra\nONLY $1.00 THE YEAR\nFOR BOTH OF THESE PAPERS\nSend in Your Subscription Today\n50c\nFor Six Months\n30c\nFor Three Months\nAddress\nSUBSCRIPTION DEPARTMENT, FARMER MECHANIC,\nRALEIGH, N. C.\nWRITKU niOM RALEIGH STRIKI08\nA BLOW AT Till: STATIC.\nSent out from llaleigh as a special\nto the New York. Times i.s an article\nthat is most unpatriotic in tone, with\nstatements in it concerning the bond\nsituation which, to u?e the imUct.\nare unwarranted by the ;cts.\nThat any Raleigh correspondent\nshould send out such an article is a\nreflection on the fraternity. It is mis\nleading all through. On Its face it\nappears that it was meant to do harm\nto the State, but that it feH fiat is\nshown by the action of the bankers on\nWednesday and the news that in New.\nYork the financiers were preparing to\ntake the entire bond issue. Head and\nall, here is what was sent out to the\nNew York Times:\nNORTH CAROLINA BOND FIX.\nState So Far Unable to Raise Money\nto Take Up Securities Due July 1.\n(Special to The New York Times.)\nRaleigh, N. C, June 5. The report\nof the action of the British Council of\nForeign Bondholders in warning in\nvestors against North Carolina bonds\non account of the repudiation of bonds\nissued many years ago, has caused a\nsensation, and will, it is feared, in\ncrease the present serious financial\ndifficulties of the State.\nBonds bearing 4 per cent interest,\namounting to $3,500,000, are due next\nJuly 1. The State has been trying to\nsell bonds at 4 per cent interest to\nraise money to take up these bonds\nand has failed. Bids were opened on\nMay 18 and only $1,200,000 was sub\nscribed. This was regarded as as\nfounding, as the total debt of the State\nis only $6,000,000 at 4 per cent, and\nthe interest has been paid promptly,\nduring the past twenty-five years.\nThe Governor and the other officers\nhave been in a panic ever since the\nbids were opened. A short time be-'\nfore that John G. Carlisle ex-Secretary,\nof the Treasury, and others issued a\nstatement attacking the credit of thd\nState because it had refused to pay\nwhat are known as the \"special tax'\nbonds,\" amounting to $20,000,000,'\nprincipal and interest, which were is\nsued in reconstruction times. It ap\npears that quite a number of the bonda\ncoming due on July 1 are held in Lon\ndon. In this emergency Governor Kitchin\nhas issued a call for the assembling of\nthe Legislature on June 14 to take\nsome aetion to protect the credit of the\nState and pay off the bonds becoming\ndue. All the bankers of the State\nhave been requested by the Governor\nto meet here next Wednesday to s&e\nif the balance of the issue cannot be\nsubscribed by bankers and other cor\nporations and individuals.\nState Treasurer Lacy thinks the\nbonds will be taken next Wednesday.\nThe bankers of this city do not think\nso. If they are not subscribed, the\nLegislature will raise the interest to\n4 1-2 per cent, which rate, it is be\nlieved, will float the entire issue. If\nthe bonds cannot be floated at the\nincreased rate, it will be proposed to\npav the increased rate on the bonds to\nthe present holders until the money\ncan be raised to redeem them.\nThe taxable property of the State is\n$500,000,000, and there is no question\nthat the interest will be promptly paid\nI CAN NOT PAY THAT PREMIUM.\nfp'rom the Man's Pat: of The Delineator.)\nBeside a frupal table, though spotless\nlean and white,\nA loving couple they did sit and all\nseemed pleasant, quite;\nThey did not have a servant the tilings\naway to take.\nFor he was hut a broker who much money\ndid not make.\n(Key changes to minor)\nHe lit a fifty-cent cigar, and then his wife\ndid say.\n\"Your life insurance it will lapse If It you\ndo net pay.\"\nlie turned from her in sorrow, for brean-\ning was his heart\nAnd in a rnezo baritone to her did say, In\n.art\nCIIORI'S- \"I can not pay that preminm,\nI'll have to let it go\nIt fills me with remorse and sorrow, not\nto mention woe.\nThough I'm quite stronpr and healthy, and\nwill outlive you, perhaps,\nI can not pay that premium, 111 have to\nlet it lapse.\"\nThe wife she naught did answer, for It cut\nher to the quick;\nShe wished the dishes, filled the lamp anJ\nlikewise trimmed the wick\nShe took in washing ih next day and\nplayed bridge whist all night.\nUntil she had enongh to pay her husband's\npremium, quite.\nThe\n(Key ebangr to minor.)\nnext day\nhusband he was thrown\nfrom his au-to-mo-bile.\nAnd although rather lonesome it did make\nhis widow feel,\nIt made her glad to know that she had\npaid that prem-i-um.\nAnd often times in after ears rhe\nwords she'd softly hum; Chorus.\nIE\n-1\n1\ni\nI\n\ni\ni\n1\nI.i\nf'1\nft\n4\nr 1\n1\nU.\nf. I\n.3.\na-\n'i","height":"34648","width":"23732"}}
